---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const topics = [
  { href: '/learn_more/using-the-website.html', title: 'Using the Website', desc: 'A guide to navigating the BeWildfireAware website, understanding FDRA pages, indicators, thresholds, forecasts, and the "Fires to Remember" section.' },
  { href: '/learn_more/fire-behavior.html', title: 'Fire Behavior Basics', desc: 'Learn about the fire triangle, the fire behavior triangle, and the key factors—fuels, topography, and weather—that influence wildfire ignition and spread.' },
  { href: '/learn_more/nfdrs.html', title: 'NFDRS Explained', desc: 'The history and workings of the National Fire Danger Rating System, including fire danger levels, pocket cards, breakpoints, and the NFDRS flowchart.' },
  { href: '/learn_more/inputs.html', title: 'Weather & Fuel Inputs', desc: 'How Remote Automated Weather Stations (RAWS), relative humidity, fuel moisture, and the Keetch-Byram Drought Index feed into fire danger calculations.' },
  { href: '/learn_more/outputs.html', title: 'NFDRS Outputs', desc: 'Detailed explanations of the Energy Release Component (ERC), Burning Index (BI), Ignition Component (IC), and Spread Component (SC).' },
  { href: '/learn_more/fuel-models.html', title: 'Fuel Models', desc: 'The five fuel model categories—Grass (V), Grass/Shrub (W), Timber (Y), Brush/Shrub (X), and Slash (Z)—and their detailed sub-model descriptions.' },
  { href: '/learn_more/terminology.html', title: 'Terminology & Restrictions', desc: 'Key wildfire terminology including federal dispatch areas, Fire Danger Rating Areas (FDRAs), and information about fire restrictions.' },
];

const levels = [
  { cls: 'green', name: 'Low', desc: 'When the fire danger is "low" it means that fuels do not ignite easily from small embers, but a more intense heat source, such as lightning, may start fires in duff or dry rotten wood. Fires in open, dry grasslands may burn easily a few hours after a rain, but most wood fires will spread slowly, creeping or smoldering. Control of fires is generally easy.' },
  { cls: 'blue', name: 'Moderate', desc: 'When the fire danger is "moderate" it means that fires can start from most accidental causes, but the number of fire starts is usually pretty low. If a fire does start in an open, dry grassland, it will burn and spread quickly on windy days. Most wood fires will spread slowly to moderately. Average fire intensity will be moderate except in heavy concentrations of fuel, which may burn hot. Fires are still not likely to become serious and are often easy to control.' },
  { cls: 'yellow', name: 'High', desc: 'When the fire danger is "high", fires can start easily from most causes and small fuels (such as grasses and needles) will ignite readily. Unattended campfires and brush fires are likely to escape. Fires will spread easily, with some areas of high-intensity burning on slopes or concentrated fuels. Fires can become serious and difficult to control unless they are put out while they are still small.' },
  { cls: 'orange', name: 'Very High', desc: 'When the fire danger is "very high", fires will start easily from most causes. The fires will spread rapidly and have a quick increase in intensity, right after ignition. Small fires can quickly become large fires and exhibit extreme fire intensity, such as long-distance spotting and fire whirls. These fires can be difficult to control and will often become much larger and longer-lasting fires.' },
  { cls: 'red', name: 'Extreme', desc: 'When the fire danger is "extreme", fires of all types start quickly and burn intensely. All fires are potentially serious and can spread very quickly with intense burning. Small fires become big fires much faster than at the "very high" level. Spot fires are probable, with long-distance spotting likely. These fires are very difficult to fight and may become very dangerous and often last for several days.' },
];
---
<Base title="Learn More - BeWildfireAware" active="learn">
  <main class="content">
    <section class="learn-more">
      <h2>Learn More About Wildfire Danger</h2>
      <p>Understanding wildfire danger helps you stay safe and make informed decisions. Explore the topics below to learn about fire behavior, the National Fire Danger Rating System, and how this website can help you assess fire risk in your area.</p>

      <div class="topic-grid">
        {topics.map((t) => (
          <a href={t.href} class="topic-card">
            <h3>{t.title}</h3>
            <p>{t.desc}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h2>Fire Danger Levels</h2>
      <p>The National Fire Danger Rating System uses five distinct levels to indicate wildfire risk. These levels are often shown on color-coded dials in parks and wildland areas.</p>

      {levels.map((l) => (
        <>
          <h2 class={`fire-danger-level ${l.cls}`}>Fire Danger Level: {l.name}</h2>
          <p>{l.desc}</p>
        </>
      ))}
    </section>
  </main>
</Base>
